<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">BIG LAW BOLSTERS BONUSES <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Big paydays for lawyers are back. Law firms are again paying hefty annual bonuses to lawyers who have put in years of working long hours on corporate deal documents, litigation papers and complex contracts, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/12/02/big-law-firms-bring-back-hefty-bonuses-for-associates">Matthew Goldstein writes in DealBook</a></b>. Associates working at a large law firm in New York are taking home, on average, from $15,000 to $100,000 in bonus payments, depending on their tenure. The top bonuses being doled out by law firms are roughly $40,000 more than most big New York firms handed out to their most senior associates last year. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe bonuses show how a <b>recovery for corporate America</b> is driving legal work on mergers and acquisitions, stock and bond offerings and intellectual property matters,â Mr. Goldstein writes. âThe higher bonuses also reflect greater spending by companies on regulatory work to comply with new rules passed after the financial crisis and with litigation driven by crisis-era lawsuits.â The bonus frenzy began a week before Thanksgiving, with a number of firms, including Simpson Thacher &#038; Bartlett, announcing plans to pay $100,000 bonuses to some associates. A few big firms â Davis Polk &#038; Wardwell and Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &#038; Flom â went even a bit higher, with Skadden announcing it would pay some senior associates bonuses of up to $110,000. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Whatâs driving the bonus bump? â<b>A look at the mergers and acquisition scorecard</b> for this year tells much of the story behind law firm bonuses,â Mr. Goldstein writes. Worldwide, companies have announced deals worth $3.2 trillion this year, a 49 percent increase from a year ago, according to Thomson Reuters. Skadden, for instance, has advised on deals worth $466 billion compared with $187 billion a year ago. It is not clear whether the six-figure bonuses being paid out by big law firms are a sign of even better times to come for lawyers, or just an aberration.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">A SCRAMBLE TO FIX EUROPEâS BANKS <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Regulators, rule makers, supervisory authorities and central banks are all jostling to fix Europeâs banking structure to prevent a future financial crisis, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/12/02/a-fragmented-confused-scramble-to-fix-europes-banking-structure">Jenny Anderson reports in DealBook</a></b>. The resulting confusion is particularly acute in London, the financial capital of Europe, which is part of the European Union, but not part of the 18-country eurozone, meaning it is subject to union laws. It is also not part of the newly minted banking union, which as of last month is to be overseen by a pan-European regulator, the Single Supervisory Mechanism.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âCaught in the middle of all this is the European Banking Authority,â Ms. Anderson writes. &#8220;<b>It is a regulator but not an enforcer</b>, and it runs high-profile stress tests on banks but cannot, by law, demand information directly from those banks. It is, at times, made out to be public enemy No. 1, even though it only writes rules for laws it did not pass. Perhaps its biggest problem is that it is housed in a shiny building in a city where many powerful players want to discredit the rules from Europe.â The authority was set up in 2010 as part of an effort to address the fragmented nature of Europeâs banking supervision. It became part of the European System of Financial Supervision, which includes four other organizations and all the national supervisory authorities.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The authorityâs main task is to <b>help create the European Single Rulebook</b>, a single set of harmonized rules for financial institutions throughout the European Union, as well as mediating disagreements among supervisors, Ms. Anderson writes. That means it has to write regulations for all the legislation that comes out of the European Union. But it operates in a crowded field. In Europe, the European Central Bank is now the single supervisor for the 18 countries in the eurozone. Nationally, regulators are asserting authority on issues from pay to tests for their banks. The recent bank stress test was also an example of the authorityâs limits. Both the European Central Bank and the banking authority ran tests.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">BANK OF NEW YORK MELLON YIELDS TO TRIAN <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Bank of New York Mellon said on Tuesday that it would give a board seat to the activist hedge fund Trian Fund Management, forestalling a potentially costly proxy fight, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/12/02/bank-of-new-york-mellon-gives-board-seat-to-trian-fund">DealBookâs Michael J. de la Merced writes</a></b>. Under the terms of the settlement, which comes days before a deadline for nominating directors, the co-founder and chief investment officer of Trian, Edward P. Garden, will join as a director. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The move, which will <b>expand Bank of New York Mellonâs board to 14 members</b>, came after several months of private discussions between the bank and Trian, after the hedge fund first disclosed owning a 2.6 percent this summer.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider"> | </span></span> <b>Big day for economic data</b>: The <b>ADP employment report</b> comes out at 8:15 a.m. Gallupâs <b>job creation index</b> is released at 8:30 a.m. The second reading of third-quarter <b>productivity and costs</b> is out at 8:30 a.m. The Markit <b>purchasing managersâ index for services</b> is released at 9:45 a.m. The Institute for Supply Management <b>nonmanufacturing index</b> comes out at 10 a.m. The Fedâs regular report on economic activity across the country, a report known as the <b>beige book</b>, is out at 2 p.m.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Lael Brainard</b>, a Fed governor, gives a speech on financial stability at 2 p.m. at the Brookings Institution in Washington.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">HOW THE BOND KING LOST EMPIRE <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Before William H. Gross abruptly left Pimco in September, he tried to hunt down employees he suspected of leaking information about internal clashes to the media. And when Mohamed A. El-Erian informed the firm in December 2013 that he was going to leave, Mr. Gross offered to step back instead (Mr. El-Erian resigned in January). Those are just some of the many details about Pimco in a <b><a href="//www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-12-02/fall-of-the-bond-king-how-gross-lost-empire-as-pimco-cracked.html">report from Bloomberg News</a></b>, which draws on interviews with 25 current and former Pimco employees. The interviews present a complex series of events that led to Mr. Grossâs departure. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Hereâs more on Mr. Grossâs mole hunt</b>: To stop media reports about clashes between Mr. El-Erian and Mr. Gross, Mr. Gross âset up interrogations of members of the  investment committee, managing directors and lower-ranking money managers,â Bloomberg News writes. Among the employees Mr. Gross believed were leaking information were Andrew Balls, one of Grossâs newly appointed deputy investment chiefs, and Joshua Thimons, an executive who had organized a going-away party for Mr. El-Erian. Mr. Gross later told Jeffrey Gundlach of DoubleLine Capital that he had been <b>chasing a âMr. X,â</b> a person sympathetic to Mr. El-Erian who was trying to sabotage him by revealing internal conversations.<br />
</p>
</div>
